<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-436-049  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 436 049.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Sept 24 1990 v7 n38 p12(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mainframe software manages PC updates. (Packet/PC Inc. Synchronyelectronic distribution and retrieval software) (productannouncement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Musich, Paula.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Packet-PC Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Synchrony 2.0 (File management software) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionMicrocomputersSoftware packagesManagement of EDP.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Mainframe Software Manages PC UpdatesandM;Where's the best place to manage the distribution and installation of PCprogram updates and the collection of PC data?andP;  The mainframe, say beta usersof Packet/PC Inc.'s Synchrony electronic distribution and retrieval software.andM;Initially developed by Packet/PC and insurance giant.andP;  The Travelers Cos.andO;for use at Travelers, Synchrony version 2.0 will be sold commercially for thefirst time beginning next month, Packet/PC officials said last week.andM;The software which consists of a Customer Information Control System (CICS)program running on an IBM System/370 mainframe and corresponding software onDOS or OS/2 PCs, automates and manages software updates for end users, italso can be used to automatically retrieve PC programs and files for centralprocessing and shared access, officials said.andM;Synchrony operates over several micro-to-mainframe links, including popular3270 coaxial emulators such as Digital Communications Associates Inc.'s IRMA;3270 programs that operate over LANs and over Synchronous Data Link Controllines; and dial-up asynchronous host links such as Packet/PC's ownPacket/3270, officials said.andM;For beta customers at Travelers, the prevalence of such links and therequirement to maintain software on hundreds of PCs around the country makeSynchrony a logical choice, according to Greg Morin, systems manager in assetmanagement and pension services for the Hartford, Conn., firm.andM;&quot;We use it for systems management and for distributed business applications,&quot;Morin said.andP;  Synchrony ensures that all Travelers employees are working withthe same release of an application and helps administrators monitor users'PCs by letting them query, for example, how much disk storage is available.andO;Travelers also maintains remote database using Synchrony.andM;&quot;Every night, data is collected from the remote databases and sent to acertain location, a master file update is run [on the mainframe] and thosetransactions are sent back to the field offices,&quot; Morin said.andM;Synchrony will be available Oct. 15 directly from Packet/PC, bsed inFarmington, Conn.andP;  It is priced at $30,000 for the host program, and from $75to $195 per PC copy.andP;  The software requires 200K bytes of memory on the PC,plus the memory required to run the micro-to-mainframe communicationssoftware.andO;</TEXT></DOC>